<br>
Unless and until Verant feels like policing the character concepts people bring to EQ (Hi!  I'm a redeemed Tier'dal working hard for Tunare!) I don't think there's much rationale for arguing the RP logic of who can be what.  Does anyone remember the very earliest days of EQ when the whole idea of Elven Paladins sent everyone into a vast debate?  Dear God!  It doesn't adhere to the D&amp;D standard!  Let's face it, people can and will play whatever the hell they want to in terms of concept.  The only limitation that's ever been imposed by the game system is class/race combination, and I can't see that that's ever succeeded in limiting absurd, annoying, original, incredible, or otherwise unusual character concepts.  <br>
<br>
I don't think the game was screaming out for new class/race combinations.  I certainly wasn't lobbying for them.  But I can't see how anything could possibly be hurt by them.  I've always believed as a gamer that people should be allowed to play what they want to play as long as it doesn't interfere with the enjoyment of others.  And I can't see how having a few SK Gnomes running around can really affect anyone else's ability to enjoy the game.  And if it does, I'm inclined to believe the problem is with the person who can't enjoy the game because somewhere, someone is playing a character they don't approve of.  Anyone who feels that way should have gotten out of a shared gaming environment a long time ago and gone back to something they have more control over.<br>
<br>
Valquiss <p><img src=http://kanina.freeservers.com/EQSketches/Valquisssig.jpg></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uforgehammer.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Forgehammer</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 26<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(3/15/02 12:02:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1540.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> I would be in favor of multi classes.</span><hr size=1> If they could figure out someway to keep it balanced. I know in the 2nd Ed. of D&amp;D theyn limited the level of the non-human races. That might be a way to get it to work. Example: Warrior decides to be a Rogue for a while. He can only get 20 levels of monk training. The logic being that above 20 requires a life commitment. This would allow a better assortment of skills in a group. I would be for allowing the melee and casters to mix. It would be too different. I see the Paladin, Shadowknight, Ranger, and Warrior on one side. Wizard, Magician, Necromancer, Enchanter on the other. The middle is the Druid, Rogue, Beastmaster, Shaman, Cleric, Monk, Bard. What you would be able to cross train would the a nieghboring class group. Warrior with Monk. Wizard with Bard. You would not be able to mix Paladin and Enchanter.<br>
<br>
