<br>
Cultural programming is probably the most virulent train of behavior that anyone has. The first memes you learn as a child are from your family/race/culture. Thus, some fields of endeavor will never be mastered by a certain cultural group (ie: there will never be a true 'American ninja master' or an 'Australian ascended yogi', and so on.) <br>
<br>
The masters of a discipline, especially in xenophobic cultures of medieval times, (upon which Tolkein Fantasy, and EQ is based) would never pass on the inner secrets (level 30+) of their Ways to a foreigner. Likewise, some cultures that have a very small minority of evil would be less likely to have any home-grown Master of Necromancy, for example. Certain classes should be inaccessible to certain characters. If you want to play a class badly, make up a character which is directly related to it. <br>
<br>
So if this idea were to translate to EQ, Gnomes would indeed be allowed to become Necromancers, Shadowknights, or Paladins.. but they would be <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> mediocre</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> at best. (limited to level 30 max) However, their Mages would certainly exceed those of any other race. So there is a nice trade-off. A good fantasy RP scenario needs this kind of balance.<br>
<br>
If you are going to have distinct races and cultures at all, this would be the result. That is the reason people scoff so much at ideas like &quot;lets make it so that halflings can be samurai&quot; (or whatever the latest class/race free-for-all is.) Putting just anything together for the hell of it wipes out any consistent campaign setting you have, and renders things to the level of Street Fighter II. <br>
<br>
~Cykranosh <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ublakkon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>blakkon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 218<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(3/15/02 3:25:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1540.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Multiclasses would be bad... </span><hr size=1> Ok here is my scenario... Play a ranger to level 9 (snare and track =100) switch to shaman... Kind of broken....<br>
